Issue 9764 : Empty metadata files should not overwrite iTunes Connect content ， Issue #9764 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub Use case: user has entered metadata (keywords  support/marketing urls  description  etc) directly into iTunes Connect for their app. user decides to try fastlane. Downloads  installs  reads the docs  inits for their app user does not bother with fastlane/metadata/ files  since that's already been done in Connect user ignores precheck missing data warnings. Again  that data is already in iTunes user runs the deliver command user finds all their metadata is gone  and is upset Feature Request / Fix: When a metadata file is empty  do not upload the empty contents and destroy the user's data. Instead  download any existing iTunes Connect data and write it into the empty file. Weak fixes: Add a WARNING to the preview.html at every blank metadata field warning the empty string will overwrite any existing data. Add a DATA DESTRUCTION note to precheck warnings when metadata is empty

Issue 10059 : REDO #9405 cert checker aborts execution if the desired certificate is already present ， Issue #10059 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I have read the Contribution Guidelines Issue Description fastlane match will fail if WWDRCA certificate is already installed in the keychain. In fastlane/fastlane_core/lib/fastlane_core/cert_checker.rb Lines 64 to 65 in 1240fe3 Helper.backticks("curl -o #{filename} #{url} && security import #{filename} #{keychain}"  print: FastlaneCore::Globals.verbose?) UI.user_error!("Could not install WWDR certificate") unless $?.success?   you can see that fastlane attempts to download https://developer.apple.com/certificationauthority/AppleWWDRCA.cer and install it in a keychain that the user has access to. It is assumed here that the nonzero exit status means the failure to import the certificate  but it does not account for the possibility the nonzero exit because the key already exists. I believe the error manifests now on Travis CI  because we added the WWDRCA certificate to our login keychain. See travis-ci/travis-ci#7870 (comment) for more context. Environment Sorry  I don't use fastlane to produce this.

Issue 10082 : issue template: fastlane's --capture_output includes Fastfile and other config files  which have Slack webhook URLs and other private credentials in them ， Issue #10082 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description When attaching fastlane output to an issue with --capture_output  I was surprised to find my full Fastfile in the output as well. I'm now changing a webhook URL and some S3 credentials as a result. While I understand that it's really useful to have these in the issue  it's also an information disclosure problem: there are usernames for match in our Matchfile  webhooks in the Fastfile  and other bits of private information in these files.

Issue 11017 : [Regression] Setting env var directly bypasses verify block ， Issue #11017 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description In our Fastfile  we define ENV["GYM_OUTPUT_NAME"] = "my_build.ipa" to globally set the output name for all of our calls to gym. This value was added to our Fastfile about 9 months ago and worked fine when cutting builds. Then recently  while trying to cut a build using Xcode 9  I was running into code signing issues during the export step - after reading through existing issues and the changelog  I found the Xcode 9 changes and promptly updated fastlane (I was using an outdated version) - problem solved. However  while the code signing error went away when I tried cutting a new build after the update  a new error appeared during our upload to hockey step - I kept hitting https://github.com/fastlane/fastlane/blob/master/fastlane/lib/fastlane/actions/hockey.rb#L179 because hockey was returning a 415: Unsupported Media Type. After some digging  I finally realized that our build was being exported with the name my_build.ipa.ipa and was surprised  since I had seen in the source that the .ipa extension was handled in order to prevent this very thing from happening when naming the build. It seems like the proc handling the GYM_OUTPUT_NAME validation (which removes the .ipa extension if present - https://github.com/fastlane/fastlane/blob/master/gym/lib/gym/options.rb#L65) was being bypassed when setting ENV["GYM_OUTPUT_NAME"] directly. Instead of setting the env var  I explicitly provided a value for output_name in our call to gym  and uploading the build to hockey succeeded without error. I'm presuming this is a regression because setting GYM_OUTPUT_NAME directly has been fine for us in the past. Environment ? fastlane environment ? Issue 11085 : [sigh] --use_app_entitlements flag with in-app-purchases/ApplePay entitlement ， Issue #11085 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description I am trying to use fastlane sigh to resign a small Apple pay demo app for testing purposes. When using the --use_app_entitlements flag  the resulting IPA crashes when trying to use the apple pay button. The issue seems to be related to permissions/entitlements. When I compare the entitlements from the original binary and the resigned one  I notce the in-app-purchases key with the corresponding merchant value is missing. This issue does not occur when not using the --use_app_entitlements flag. From my limiting understanding the blacklist that is provided in the resign.sh script removes this entitlement with the --use_app_entitlement flag. But there seems to be no real explanation as to why. The only thing I could find is a link to a buck issue regarding acceptance by the apple store. But to me it seems that this entitlement should still be in there for the app to run. Fastlane env ? fastlane environment ? Since device_manager.rb is checking for next if line =~ /unavailable/ only  it counts this booted simulator as one of the "good" one and tries to get exact version for it from runtimes dictionary and ends up with com.apple.CoreSimulator.SimRuntime.iOS-11-2. I can't tell exactly how did I manage to have unavailable simulator in booted state. Must be related to the fact that I have multiple Xcode versions on my laptop. The workaround using xcrun simctl shutdown Simulator-ID or xcrun simctl shutdown all is always possible  though I think Fastlane can also add some safety checks  e.g. skip whole group of unavailable devices  which may be easier after switching to --json ouptut of simctl. Issue 11420 : Spaceship::Tunes::AppVersion.current_build_number is incorrect ， Issue #11420 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub AppVersion current_build_number doesn't return the latest submitted build. Specifically it takes the very first candidate build for edit version and candidate builds are not upload-time sorted (it turns out). fastlane/spaceship/lib/spaceship/tunes/app_version.rb Lines 315 to 323 in 7171725 def current_build_number if self.is_live? build_version else if candidate_builds.length > 0 candidate_builds.first.build_version end end end probably something like: def current_build_number     if self.is_live?       build_version     else       if candidate_builds.length > 0         candidate_builds.sort_by(&:upload_date).last.build_version      end     end   end

Issue 11659 : Certificate not installed when already installed in other keychain ， Issue #11659 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description I'm implementing the fastlane match action to use in our build script for Xamarin iOS builds (using terminal commands). When the certificate is not installed on the machine  this works correctly. However  if the certificate is already installed in another keychain  the certificate is not installed in the provided keychain. This is problematic: for each build  a new keychain is created and the certificate added; the keychain is removed when the build is completed. If multiple builds need the same certificate  the latter build will fail if the first build removed its keychain. The main issue is this error: security: SecKeychainItemImport: The specified item already exists in the keychain. It thinks the certificate is already installed in the keychain  while it isn't. Issue 11721 : deliver exports screenshots from iTC as JPEG  saves them as PNG ， Issue #11721 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description When first using deliver and it pulls down the metadata from iTC  it downloads the screenshots and saves them with a .png extension. However iTC appears to be serving JPEG images  so we end up with screenshots in JPEG format but the png extension. When deliver tries to upload these again to iTC it fails  with the confusing error message: [14:48:56]: [IMG_BAD_COLOR_SPACE] This does not use RGB color space. Please edit the image to use the RGB color space and re-save it.  The color space is in fact correct  the format (for the stated extension) is incorrect. It is unclear whether this is a fastlane/deliver bug or a change in iTC. I checked the formats of the "png" files that deliver saved when initialising: marc$ identify fastlane/screenshots/en-US/*.png fastlane/screenshots/en-US/1_ipadPro_1.ipad-pro-store.png JPEG 2048x2732 2048x2732+0+0 8-bit sRGB 533310B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/1_ipad_1.ipad-store.png JPEG 1536x2048 1536x2048+0+0 8-bit sRGB 334928B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/1_iphone6Plus_1.iphone-store.png JPEG 1242x2208 1242x2208+0+0 8-bit sRGB 229927B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/2_ipadPro_2.ipad-pro-share.png JPEG 2048x2732 2048x2732+0+0 8-bit sRGB 402192B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/2_ipad_2.ipad-share.png JPEG 1536x2048 1536x2048+0+0 8-bit sRGB 262801B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/2_iphone6Plus_2.iphone-find (1).png JPEG 1242x2208 1242x2208+0+0 8-bit sRGB 284442B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/3_ipadPro_3.ipad-pro-comment.png JPEG 2048x2732 2048x2732+0+0 8-bit sRGB 395176B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/3_ipad_3.ipad-comment.png JPEG 1536x2048 1536x2048+0+0 8-bit sRGB 243573B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/3_iphone6Plus_3.iphone-share.png JPEG 1242x2208 1242x2208+0+0 8-bit sRGB 187988B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/4_ipadPro_4.ipad-pro-find.png JPEG 2048x2732 2048x2732+0+0 8-bit sRGB 533208B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/4_ipad_4.ipad-find.png JPEG 1536x2048 1536x2048+0+0 8-bit sRGB 338265B 0.000u 0:00.000 fastlane/screenshots/en-US/4_iphone6Plus_4.iphone-comment.png JPEG 1242x2208 1242x2208+0+0 8-bit sRGB 168436B 0.000u 0:00.000  You can see they are all JPEG sRGB  not PNG. The workaround is to get the original PNGs again and save them over these bad images. However I notice in iTC web UI that the screenshots are displayed as JPEGs. If this is the same endpoint spaceship is using  then this would appear to be the source of the problem. It seems like quite a bad bug in that the deliver init process is no longer symmetrical - you can download but cannot upload that same data.

Issue 11768 : deliver downloads `app_icon` from iTC as a JPEG  uploads as JPEG causing iTC error ， Issue #11768 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description Investigating a fix for #11724 that turns out was not "needed" (it seems iTC allows JPEG uploads of screenshots and even if they are called .png)  I found that the real problem I had was that the app icon was downloaded by deliver as a JPEG and saved as app_icon.jpg which makes some sense if iTC is serving up JPEGs these days. However when you deliver to the app store  the JPEG icon is uploaded and you get the bad colorspace crash as it seems to expect a PNG as you would hope for quality reasons. bundler: failed to load command: fastlane (/usr/local/lib/ruby/gems/2.4.0/bin/fastlane) Spaceship::UnexpectedResponse: [!] [IMG_BAD_COLOR_SPACE] This does not use RGB color space. Please edit the image to use the RGB color space and re-save it.   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/spaceship/lib/spaceship/du/du_client.rb:160:in `parse_upload_response'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/spaceship/lib/spaceship/du/du_client.rb:96:in `upload_file'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/spaceship/lib/spaceship/du/du_client.rb:29:in `upload_large_icon'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/spaceship/lib/spaceship/tunes/tunes_client.rb:663:in `upload_large_icon'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/spaceship/lib/spaceship/tunes/app_version.rb:446:in `upload_large_icon!'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/deliver/lib/deliver/upload_assets.rb:16:in `upload'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/deliver/lib/deliver/runner.rb:126:in `upload_metadata'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/deliver/lib/deliver/runner.rb:39:in `run'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/actions/upload_to_app_store.rb:16:in `run'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/runner.rb:253:in `block (2 levels) in execute_action'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/actions/actions_helper.rb:50:in `execute_action'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/runner.rb:231:in `block in execute_action'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/runner.rb:227:in `chdir'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/runner.rb:227:in `execute_action'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/runner.rb:148:in `trigger_action_by_name'   /Users/marc/Projects/checkout/fastlane/fastlane/lib/fastlane/fast_file.rb:148:in `method_missing'   Fastfile:119:in `block (2 levels) in parsing_binding'  So there appear to be two related issues: App icon is downloaded from iTC as JPEG and saved as app_icon.jpg  which probably isn't desired When uploading the metadata  deliver is "smart" and uses either app_icon.jpg  or app_icon.png whichever exists. This seems wrong as iTC chokes on a JPEG Aside: Interestingly it seems there is some significantly divergent asset handling in the codepath. Why are JPEG screenshots downloaded (without choking on this?) and then saved as .png  whereas the app icon is downloaded as a JPEG (should also choke on this?) and then saves as .jpg. It feels like there should be unified safe handling of this.

Issue 11858 : Couldn't decrypt the repo when using swift in syncCodeSigning ， Issue #11858 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description I have been using fastlane for some months and have correctly setup match for code signing. Now I'm trying to upgrate to the new swift language feature so I'm "translating" the ruby script to be in swift and use the FastlaneRunner with the generated xcode project and so. The issue I'm having is that when running the syncCodeSigning function it throws an error saying that the password is wrong when i'm sure it is correct. Then I run plain 'fastlane run match' and introduce the same params when asked (git url  password) and it successfully decrypts the certificates and everything works fine. The only difference I can see is that one is run from old-way ruby and the other is from swift and goes through all the RubyCommand.Argument stuff. When using old-way ruby it works and when using swift it doesn't.

Issue 11872 : Lane latest_testflight_build_number does not handle iTunesConnect error "There was an error importing this build." ， Issue #11872 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description Running: fastlane run latest_testflight_build_number version:3.1.7 --capture_output When the latest build on iTunesConnect has a "There was an error importing this build."  it returns the build number before the last one. Meaning  when the last build was 4 but failed due to error "There was an error importing this build."  it return the build number 3. This  after incrementing the build number to latest_testflight_build_number + 1  makes my pilot command fail with the error: "Redundant Binary Upload. There already exists a binary upload with build '4' for version '3.1.7'" The lane latest_testflight_build_number should return the latest build number no matter the state it is at. In my case  it should return 4 and not 3. Issue 12081 : upload_symbols_to_crashlytics action fails on unzip errors ， Issue #12081 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description For some of my projects with bitcode support iTunes Connect provides archived dSYMs which cannot be unzipped properly  at least it seems like that. Every time upload_symbols_to_crashlytics tries to invoke unzip command it fails with invalid byte sequence in UTF-8 error message  but  in fact  some of the dSYMs were actually unzipped. However  since unzip returns an error code instead of 0 sh action throws an error  so none of those successfully unzipped dSYMs are going to be uploaded. I've ran some tests in terminal with unzip -qo and manually downloaded dSYMs  just to make sure this is not the problem of download_dsyms or any other part of Fastlane. So  my question is: could we add some kind of fail_on_unzip_errors parameter which will be set to true by default to upload_symbols_to_crashlytics action and wrap Actions.sh("unzip -qo #{current_path.shellescape}") with begin/rescue block? Something like this: begin   Actions.sh("unzip -qo #{current_path.shellescape}") rescue => ex   UI.user_error!(ex.to_s) if params[:fail_on_unzip_errors] end Maybe there is a better way to workaround the problem I have  but It would be better if upload_symbols_to_crashlytics could handle such situations by itself. Thanks in advance! Issue 12132 : Upload to Crashlytics plugin has no way to disable Firebase plist upload ， Issue #12132 ， fastlane/fastlane ， GitHub New Issue Checklist Updated fastlane to the latest version I read the Contribution Guidelines I read docs.fastlane.tools I searched for existing GitHub issues Issue Description Recently  UploadSymbolsToCrashlyticsAction was updated to support the relatively new feature of uploading symbols to Fabric using a GoogleServices plist file (#11798). While this is listed as an optional setting  if there is a GoogleServices.plist file anywhere in the directory structure  the action will now attempt to upload using the plist. Unfortunately  this causes problems in multi-organization scenarios for Fabric. Firebase doesn't currently support having different configurations within the same app (to support things like enterprise versions or internal versions)  so there is only one plist file. At the same time  uploading to Fabric with the plist overrides any value used for the Fabric App ID. What this results in is that the dSYM files can be uploaded to the wrong Fabric Organization  which will result in crashes being unable to be symbolicated. This action should be update to truly make the GoogleServices plist optional and not pull it in automatically if found. We have created a workaround by replicating the previous version of the UploadSymbolsToCrashlyticsAction as a local action and using the local action instead of the real action  but we would prefer using the official action  if possible.
